text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!SignLanguage]]%0a%0a!Cochlear Implants%0a%0a:Author: sathyas%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWhat are cochlear implants, how do they work, and what is the controversy regarding them?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aWhat is are Cochlear Implants and how do they work?%0a%0aA Cochlear Implant (will refer to as CI) is an electronic device used to help restore hearing in people suffering from severe hearing loss to the extent where a hearing aid is no longer useful. While hearing aids are external devices used to amplify sound, CIs require surgical implantation. They work by bypassing damaged areas and "directly simulating the auditory nerve". Deaf people are unable to hear because of a damaged cochlea (auditory nerve), which is essentially replaced by the CI. The signals are then sent down the path of the auditory nerve to the brain which can then identify and process as sound. The audio heard through a CI is different than that of the natural auditory nerve and takes time to adapt, but it can allow deaf individuals to hear environment sounds and listen/understand to speech once trained.%0a%0aSo why are CIs controversial within the deaf community?%0a%0aThe deaf community perceives CIs as a insult to their community as they feel that they are already able to live full capable and functional lives. Thus, they feel that having deaf children receive CIs is a threatening act from the hearing majority towards the deaf minority. The deaf community's perception is that nothing needs to be fixed, and our perception (the hearing community) is that something needs to be fixed and we should assist them. It spreads the idea that this group of people needs "fixing". Deaf culture is like any other minority group and would like to preserve itself to maintain a supportive community.%0a%0aAnother controversial aspect of CIs is that they are not a miracle cure as many hearing individuals view it as. The initial installation is very mentally taxing and exhaustive, ringing background noises are often common until the brain adapts, certain environments are still difficult to hear in, and some users may never be able to fully understand conversation. Lastly, many hearing parents will often fail to teach their deaf child ASL once a cochlear is installed following the belief that it is a miracle cure.%0a%0aCochlear Implants threaten the deaf community by indicating that they need fixing and are often not an ideal solution to deafness. These reasons cause CIs to be controversial amongst the deaf community.%0a%0ahttps://www.cbsnews.com/news/the-cochlear-implant-controversy/#:~:text=The%2520culture%2520rebelled%2520against%2520attempts,to%2520be%2520their%2520native%2520language. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6913847/ https://www.insider.com/why-deaf-people-turn-down-cochlear-implants-2016-12%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210506-005220-754260#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Same Controversy Present in Spoken Languages %0a-> - sirisha_b%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI think it is interesting to point out that a common thing hearing people may say to people who are deaf is "Oh, don't you want to be able to hear?  It will make your life easier." with the assumption that if we were to put hearing and deaf on a scale, hearing would always be better and cause less problems for that person.  First of all, this isn't true, especially if being deaf is what the person is familiar and comfortable with.  But that is only because we live in a world that has more hearing people and is mainly tailored for hearing people without considering the needs of those in the deaf community.%0aThe same phenomenon can be seen for speakers of other languages aside from English, or those who don't have a standardized American accent.  People who are in the majority will tell those who aren't that it is better to make the change, but they completely disregard that what seems different to them is completely normal to others.  As a society, we need to get better at accommodating to the needs of everyone and acknowledging that different is never worse when it comes to differences in language.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-005220-754260#%0a#foxbegin 210506-050214-93160#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Two Considerations on Cochlear Implants %0a-> - VikramM%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aWhile researching for the linguistic discrimination in the wild category, I came across discussion of the bias in the medical field in favor of cochlear implants. In the discussion about discrimination in medicine for users of ASL, there was also mention of how the medical field views cochlear implants nearly solely, possibly understandably so, as a device to fix an issue. While this may be one perspective on the issue, making sure everyone involved in the decision-making process has a full understanding on what having a cochlear implant means for the user, the deaf community, and others closely involved is an important step in the process.%0a%0aA second consideration with the cochlear implant is equal distribution among those who wish to have one. In data from the US and UK about implants, there was evidence to suggest that the distribution and use of cochlear implants is not equal and that socioeconomic standing and race can play a role. Health insurance differences could also significantly affect this situation. Unequal distribution could potentially exacerbate existing issues with socioeconomic divisions in society. %0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://academic.oup.com/jdsde/article/11/1/102/410842%0ahttps://www-jstor-org.cmu.idm.oclc.org/stable/pdf/3528774.pdf?%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-050214-93160#%0a#foxbegin 210506-050237-593140#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Two Considerations on Cochlear Implants %0a-> - VikramM%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aWhile researching for the linguistic discrimination in the wild category, I came across discussion of the bias in the medical field in favor of cochlear implants. In the discussion about discrimination in medicine for users of ASL, there was also mention of how the medical field views cochlear implants nearly solely, possibly understandably so, as a device to fix an issue. While this may be one perspective on the issue, making sure everyone involved in the decision-making process has a full understanding on what having a cochlear implant means for the user, the deaf community, and others closely involved is an important step in the process.%0a%0aA second consideration with the cochlear implant is equal distribution among those who wish to have one. In data from the US and UK about implants, there was evidence to suggest that the distribution and use of cochlear implants is not equal and that socioeconomic standing and race can play a role. Health insurance differences could also significantly affect this situation. Unequal distribution could potentially exacerbate existing issues with socioeconomic divisions in society. %0a%0aSources: %0ahttps://academic.oup.com/jdsde/article/11/1/102/410842%0ahttps://www-jstor-org.cmu.idm.oclc.org/stable/pdf/3528774.pdf?%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210506-050237-593140#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210512-160800-982460#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-12.05.2021 - 09:08-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210512-160800-982460 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!MarkC%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Baby Sister and Cochlear Implants'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aMy baby sister who is around 8 months old, was born partially deaf, and my parents are currently debating whether to have her get a cochlear implant. The surgery can be done at around 10-12 months old. Apparently the argument for early surgery is that the child will be able to use the implant to perceive sounds at an early age. However, this is problematic in my opinion, as the child isn't old enough to decide for themselves what they want to do, and thus it is up to the parents to make a choice that may define and change their child's identity forever. Whether this is moral or not is a hard question to answer. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210512-160800-982460#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: SignLanguage:)
